 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://members.hometown.aol.com/_ht_a/naturyl/images/YinYangsblack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 132<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/24/02 2:58:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=89.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Which country is more likely to build an Orion?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; China could go it alone for pure political posturing<br>
reasons, but I think they want into the global economy.<br>
&gt; Trying to do a surface to orbit Orion unilaterally would<br>
likely cost them more than they'd gain. Chinese space<br>
stations, missions to the Moon or Mars only serve to<br>
increase China's international status, nothing more. For<br>
a definitive example look at the Apollo program.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 Forget Apollo. There's enough proof that there's profitability in space, and ways to use space resources to lengthen your stay -even permanently- that nobody is going to do another one-shot. Maybe I'm too optimistic, but I think the Chinese are too pragmatic to just do a Lunar landing, and then turn their backs on all of space just because they'd made some headlines. (&quot;The glorious accomplishment of the People shows once and for all that the obscene capitalistic ways ot the US aren't the way of the future. The cooperation of the People has established a foothold in the heavens, while the US couldn't do anything besides go around in circles in LEO for 30 years!&quot;)<br>
<br>
Second, we are talking about an Orion ground launch, and that would get a fully self-sufficient mine/base on an NEA in one shot.<br>
A space-assembled ship would put a basic survival station and beginning mine/base in place, surely pointing towards bigger things in the future.<br>
<br>
Far from &quot;doing a surface to orbit Orion unilaterally costing them more than they'd gain&quot;, I'll suggest that it would grant them instant superiority! If they put up an armed space battle station it would play hell, but a permanently crewed mine/base at Mars' moons or an NEA would give them <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> leadership</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of the global economy! Space access gives tremendous strategic superiority as well, They wouldn't need to use refined fissionables for weapons when they can drop rocks!<br>
<br>
 I'm not entirely familiar with the spectroscopic studies of Eros which were mentioned here, but it's old news. Water gives you space. The metals freely floating around in space give you the world economy. The other nations and companies are cutting their own throats if they don't jump into space with both feet.<br>
 Given what is known today, there are very few ways a mission could be done that wouldn't pay off several national debts, let alone pay off the mission investment. (Count on NASA to find the way to make it crash...)<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
<br>
I wasn't able to answer the poll because it didn't have a check for multi-national cooperation.<br>
<br>
 Let China prove that they have the technology &amp; lasting will to put people on the Moon, and do something besides flags &amp; footprints.<br>
 The rest of the world would get scared silly, and something like the CDIs suggestion for an internationally controlled system would arise. Use up the Pu to guarantee it won't go into weapons, establish international cooperation (which is obviously needed to further Orion in every step of the effort), and send up a big one (if the US declassifies &quot;fusion-only clean&quot; bombs; either a Single HLV shot or maybe even a surface launch, if it's safe)<br>
