 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://members.hometown.aol.com/_ht_a/naturyl/images/YinYangsblack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 148<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/14/02 10:48:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=89.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/Cyberia/Cosmos/Images/northsouth_lg.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Who knows?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; Do </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->(Fusion-only &quot;clean&quot; bombs)<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  actually<br>
exist? I thought the energy needed to initiate a<br>
fusion reaction in a bomb required the power of<br>
a fission explosion?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 So far. The DOD is supposedly interested in them, because relatively clean, sub-kilotonne bombs make nuclear weapons &quot;more acceptable&quot; -meaning nobody would object too strenuously if we used them on bunkers in Iraq (or whoever is the enemy of the moment).<br>
Inertial confinement doesn't look too favorable, even in a lab, let alone a field-deployable small weapon (or an NPR ship's engine).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; If they do exist, even if only on paper, how<br>
clean... would a fusion bomb be? zero harmful<br>
radiation?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I suspect that there would be some pollution from the structure and other stuff involved in a bomb. Still, it would be far less nasty than a fission trigger.<br>
Maybe it'd be possible to use different materials, which minimizes lingering radiation. Anything we can say or expect to hear about it is speculative, because the only real data is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> extremely</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> classified...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; This would be great news for an Orion type<br>
ground launch, except for the EMP.<br>
&gt; Of course the article at NS covers the EMP effect<br>
to some degree.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I objected to the basic premise that EMP is a consideration: Everything we know says that EMP is caused by extremely huge bursts (several MT plus), or maybe very much smaller bursts, which are specially designed to maximize it (directed, enhanced gamma production?).<br>
 Orion thrust bombs are very small, and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> not</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> designed to maximize it, or maybe designed to minimize it. It just doesn't seem to be a big consideration.<br>
<br>
 Minimize gammas, to minimize EMP, with maximum possible prompt heat flash relative to all other effects, to provide the most energy to the propellant injected into the explosion.<br>
 We know that fairly clean, small bombs can be made to maximize neutrons. I don't know if that helps an Orion any, but it does indicate that there's a wide variety of possible bomb designs for different effects.<br>
It doesn't bother us if there's an intense prompt flash of radiation. The ship itself is protected, and there's nothing else nearby to be hurt. We obviously don't use stuff like cobalt jackets to maximize lingering radiation! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ustifled.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Stifled</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 13<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/15/02 12:10:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=89.topic&index=25>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Who knows?</span><hr size=1> In an Orion bomb, you wish to maximise x-rays.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubrp17.showPublicProfile?language=EN>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 78<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/15/02 12:11:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=89.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Who knows?</span><hr size=1> So far. The DOD is supposedly interested in them, because relatively clean, sub-kilotonne bombs make nuclear weapons &quot;more acceptable&quot; -meaning nobody would object too strenuously if we used them on bunkers in Iraq (or whoever is the enemy of the moment).<br>
Inertial confinement doesn't look too favorable, even in a lab, let alone a field-deployable small weapon (or an NPR ship's engine).<br>
<br>
Pure fusion bombs have been under development since the first thermonuclear bombs, and to date there is only 2 ways to achieve the required fusion explosion, through a fission trigger, and through an extremely intense laser. Wait, there is one other, now that I think about it. Most nuclear bombs today use a fusion trigger to start a fission trigger to start a fusion trigger. Confused yet? Inside the innermost layer of a nuclear bombs, there is usually a certain level of deudarium/tritium that's purpose is to create enough neutrons to start the fission reaction. However, this method has an upper limit, very small amounts can be used. In fact, it probably produces less explosion than the chemical trigger, but I'm not certain of that. Well, those are the 3 methods. Experiments have been tested using sound waves, although thus far they are unproven. Hmmm. Perhaps I can come up with an article on this subject... Hmmm. As to radiation coming from them, it is mostly in the form of gamma/neutron radiation, not the far more damagine alpha/beta/vaporized radioactive materials that are produced in a fission trigger. Wait, I forgot yet another method, Anti-matter triggered, but there isn't a way to trap anti-matter enough to start this system yet.<br>
<br>
As to EMP, well, look at it like this. I am probably one of the leading experts on how an Orion would cause EMP that doesn't have classified information. AFAIK, I'm the only person in history to even attempt to tackle it. If you haven't already, read my article on the main page of nuclearspace.com . Fission bombs today are relatively easy to make, but large thermonuclear are much harder to detect. There is only 1 US nuclear test that defitively defines the bounds of EMP, and that is very limited. In 1963, the Starfish Prime nuclear test, a 1.4 Megaton thermonuclear warhead was launched to a height of 400 miles above an island, the name of which escapes me, 800 miles away from Hawaii, caused signifigant damage in terms of electromagnetic pulse shockwaves throught Hawaii, and that was before the wide spread use of many technological wonders today, computers, televisions, transister radios, etc. Based on the fact that this was an ocean, there was virtually boundry assigned, other than it caused damage at 800 miles. Farther away, the nearest island which had the electronic devices was about 1600 miles away, and they reported little damage, although I believe even at this distance away there was some static caused in radio waves, or something to that effect. EMP is virtually impossible to quantify, unless a test was done to prove exactly what area would be impacted, or you have access to top-secret programs that define EMP. I am currently undergoing research with a friend of mine, Dr. Temenoujka Fuller, who recieved a masters working in EMP due to cosmic radiation, and has her Ph.D. in nuclear physics. She developed a computer program that tests EMP, the problem was that it was half-way across the world from where we live. Not to mention that the data involved in nuclear research is largely untested.<br>
<br>
There are two complications as to why EMP due to a fission bomb is unknown. First of all, the government doesn't want you to know. Actually, it's not you, but those small governments that may have a nuclear bomb in existance. Imagine if it were known that a smaller nuclear bomb could cause wide Electromagnetic pulse. Terrorists would have them launched, it would cause chaos. The second is the difference between a fission bomb and a thermonuclear bomb. Fission bombs produce far more radiation than thermonuclear bombs for their explosive capabilities. And as it is the radiation that causes EMP, not the destructive power, then the relative EMP for a fission bomb would be increased by a probably classified factor. For simplicity in my paper, I ignored this factor.<br>
<br>
Orion is very seemingly researched, but the truth is, it's not as easy to minimize certain factors as you would think. Of course, I'm no nuclear scientist. Remember this however, it's been almost 20 years since any real kinds of nuclear tests have been performed, aside from third world countries testing their primative weapons, and it's been 40 years since any real atmospheric weapons testing was performed. It would take a great deal of time to regain the skills we once had in manipulating nuclear bombs.<br>
<br>
As for a third world country building an Orion, I would agree, it would be very difficult for any country to disguse the efforts of building a more than a small number of nuclear bombs. To give you an idea, the first uranium refining factories were miles upon miles long. Natural uranium is very easy to obtain, it's one of the cheapest elements avaliable. However, enriched uranium is very difficult to obtain, and it's value is enormous, I don't have the exact figures, but I think it's in the tens of thousands of dollars per pound. Maybe it's gone down somewhat, I'm not really sure.It's extrodinarily difficult to refine Uranium. Plutonium, which would be the better source for such a thing, would be similarly difficult to produce. Stealing it from reactor programs doesn't make sense either, most reactors have 40%- enriched uranium, in fact, most are around 10%. I think plutonium is similar statistics. The more plutonium is put into a reactor, the less is usable for weapons statistics. All of this information leaves in my opinion to the abolishing of a third world country building an Orion unknown is virtually nothing. A satilite would easily detect the building of the required production plants, the radiation levels would be detectable from space, and as a whole it would be very unlikely.<br>
<br>
As to Yales comment, you want to maximize what's known as soft x-rays, which are generally a production of heat. At least, that's how I always understood it. Gamma rays are in need to be reduced, as well as most forms of radiation.<br>
<br>
Well, I think I've written enough of a paper. Any responses anyone? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utim1965.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tim1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/15/02 2:41:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=89.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Who knows?</span><hr size=1> Israel may ultimately be the most likely nation to build an orion class np drive  spacecraft. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2340<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/27/02 3:04:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=89.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Who knows?</span><hr size=1> Where would they launch it from? Palestine?<br>
