<br>
If compared on a similer scale, ie around the size of NASA's Reference Mission, one can easily compaire the three. An ion drive would have an Isp of around 30000s and a thrust of 30N, VASMIR will produce an Isp of 3000-30000s with corisponding thrusts of 1200-40N. An EPPP could give an Isp of 3000s with a thrust of 16000000N. Over 1000 times the thrust of VASMIR for the same efficiency, that is why we like ORION.<br>
<br>
NERVA has existed for 40 years as usible technology, with almost twice the efficency of chemical rockets. It is usible today without signifigent developement.<br>
<br>
The developement of any of them is much supported, the is no bad form of nuclear power to expand human presence in space. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1361<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/6/02 9:05:17 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=89.topic&index=33>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Why orion?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>...there is no bad form of nuclear power to expand human presence in space. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
